I found six Scaphiopus on back roads in Bastrop County (Park Road 1C and Gotier Trace Road) on 3-21-20.   I am posting four iNat records, including this one and three others.  To me they look intermediate between S. hurterii and S. couchii, and I'm wondering if they could be hybrids. Certain characteristics look like couchii to me, including the dominant yellow coloration and the very slight boss between the eyes (or absence of).  I only heard one spadefoot calling, but was unable to get a recording.

Weather at the time was air temperature mid-50s, light rain falling after heavier rain earlier that day, light north wind, barometric pressure 30.22 in Hg.

This little one was alone, as far as I could tell. At Milagro there is an area in a small wash that runs through our property that fills up and creates a temporary pond during monsoon season. Many, many spadefoots surface there and mate and then disappear. We have found stray ones inside our fenced area (to keep the javelina out) but usually they surface the same time the pond fills up. I was very surprised to see one during this  dry June.

There was a lot of vibration close by  from jackhammers used for resurfacing the community pool. I wonder if that might have affect it.

"Scaphiopus holbrookii spends almost all of its life deep underground; coming out only to breed, and sometimes eat. It remains in a type of hibernation almost all its life. It burrows in a spiral, preferring sandy soils.

Research has looked into the habitat selection of the species, and has found that it tends to hover around upland areas. It has shown preference for being close to deciduous shrub edges, low-growing pitch pine branches, and reindeer lichen. This environment provides an easy place to burrow land, with dense prey biomass, and protection from predators.[5]

Conservation status

While not listed as an endangered species by the U.S. federal government, S. holbrookii is considered "threatened" in Massachusetts.[6] In that state and in 13 others, it is listed as a "Species of Greatest Conservation Need"."

Full story and disclaimer. My dad was coming home from work in a thunderstorm and this road had dozens of toads crossing it. Hey brought them home for two reasons, there was a ton of traffic and surely his kids want to see them. These toads were the only live ones left as when spadefoots are threatened, they hunker down instead of hopping away, making them easy targets for mindless drivers. 25 toads were rescued overall including one chorus frog. The following morning, we went to a private pond a couple miles away from the rescue point. It was similar habitat and we had heard spadefoot croaking there before. In this location, they won't have the threat of being attacked by vehicles.

Was leaving a friend's home last night and it caught my eye on her walkway. It had been raining earlier in the day. I picked it up thinking it was a very common pacific tree frog, but soon realized it was a small toad. It was beginning to freeze with ice developing on its skin. My husband and I are both Environmental Scientists and noticed the vertical pupil and the spade on the two hind feet. We were very surprised to see it. The toad began moving with the warmth of our hands and we placed him in a nearby ground squirrel borrow, with the hope that it would find shelter there.
The occurrence was by Mill Creek in Wonder Valley CA. We lived there 7 years and never saw a spadefoot before.

The Sonoran Desert Toad is also known as the Colorado River Toad. It is known for it being able to release toxins from glands within its skin and these toxins have psychoactive properties. They are also known for being deadly to dogs. They are able to have as many as 8000 eggs in a single strand. They typically live 2-4 years. If you are trying to control them and keep them out of your yard remove hideouts and water or food sources. Toads like dark damp places so avoid having these in your backyard especially if you have dogs. 

Sonoran desert toads are also poisonous to humans and it is highly recommended not to touch them. You will typically see them in the summer around monsoons but you can see them at other times of the year as well.

Of the three species of spadefoots occurring in New Mexico (genera Scaphiopus and Spea) this individual's identification is based on the absence of a boss between the eyes and it having an odor reminiscent of peanuts, both features eliminating Plains Spadefoot (Spea bombifrons). Unlike the sickle-shaped "spade" of Couch's Spadefoot (Scaphiopus couchii) this individual's "spade" is wedge-shaped.
